eotypes and images of Indigenous people, contest white supremacy and heteropatriarchy, and reconstruct ideas of a progressive masculinity. In addition, this book carefully traces the idea of authenticity; that is, the common notion that, by engaging in a Black culture, Indigenous people are losing their "traditions." Indigenous hip hop artists navigate the muddy waters of the "politics of authenticity" by creating art that is not bound by narrow conceptions of what it means to be Indigenous; instead, they flip the notion of "tradition" and create alternative visions of what being Indigenous means today, and what that might look like going forward.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aHip-hopzNorth America. 0aIndian youthzNorth AmericaxMusic. 0aIndians of North AmericaxMusicxHistory and criticism. 0aRap (Music)xHistory and criticism. 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 4aAmerican Studies : Indigenous Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Popular Culture. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Music. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2018z978311149142440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438469478423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438469478/original  a978-3-11-149142-4  SUNY Press eBook Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles